definitions.definition: A combination of events which have come together by chance to make a surprisingly good or wonderful outcome.
An unsought, unintended, and/or unexpected, but fortunate, discovery and/or learning experience that happens by accident.
The mental ability to recover quickly from depression, illness or misfortune.
The physical property of material that can resume its shape after being stretched or deformed; elasticity.

The positive capacity of an organizational system or company to adapt and return to equilibrium due to the consequences of a crisis or failure caused by any type of disruption, including: an outage, natural disasters, man-made disasters, terrorism, or similar (particularly IT systems, archives).
Something which lasts for a short period of time.
Lasting for a short period of time.
Existing for only one day, as with some flowers, insects, and diseases.
(of a body of water) Usually dry, but filling with water for brief periods during and after precipitation.
Lasting for only a moment.
Happening at every moment; perpetual.
Ephemeral or relatively short-lived.
To float.
To pass over rapidly; to skim the surface of.

definitions.definition: To hasten over; to cause to pass away lightly, or in mirth and joy.
To flee, to escape, to speed away.
To evanesce, disappear, die out.
To move up a rope, so as to haul to more advantage; especially to draw apart the blocks of a tackle.
(of people) To move or change in position.
To shift the position of dead-eyes when the shrouds are become too long.
To cause to slip down the barrel of a capstan or windlass, as a rope or chain.
To take the cream from; to skim.
Passing quickly; of short duration.

definitions.definition: Something that happens to someone by chance, a chance occurrence, especially a favourable one.

definitions.definition: A superstitious feeling that brings fortune or success.

definitions.definition: Success.

definitions.definition: The results of a random number generator.

definitions.definition: To rely on luck.

definitions.definition: Something being indicated that is there; one of those.
(degree) To a given extent or degree.
definitions.example: "The ribbon was that thin." "I disagree, I say it was not that thin, it was thicker... or maybe thinner..."

definitions.definition: (degree) To a great extent or degree; very, particularly (in negative constructions).
definitions.example: I did the run last year, and it wasn't that difficult.

definitions.definition: To such an extent; so. (in positive constructions).
definitions.example: Ooh, I was that happy I nearly kissed her.

definitions.definition: (demonstrative) The thing, person, idea, quality, event, action or time indicated or understood from context, especially if more remote geographically, temporally or mentally than one designated as "this", or if expressing distinction.
definitions.example: He went home, and after that I never saw him again.

definitions.definition: The known (thing); used to refer to something just said.
definitions.example: They're getting divorced. What do you think about that?

definitions.definition: (demonstrative) The aforementioned quality or proposition; used to emphatically affirm or deny a previous statement or question.
definitions.example: The water is so cold! — That it is.

definitions.definition: (relative) (plural that) Which, who; representing a subject, direct object, indirect object, or object of a preposition.
definitions.example: The CPR course that she took really came in handy.

definitions.definition: Used in place of relative adverbs such as where or when; often omitted.
definitions.example: the last time that [= when] I went to Europe

definitions.definition: Introducing a clause which is the subject or object of a verb (such as one involving reported speech), or which is a complement to a previous statement.
definitions.example: He told me that the book is a good read.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause expressing a reason or cause: because, in that.
definitions.example: Be glad that you have enough to eat.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause that expresses an aim, purpose or goal ("final"), and usually contains the auxiliaries may, might or should: so, so that.
Introducing — especially, but not exclusively, with an antecedent like so or such — a subordinate clause expressing a result, consequence or effect.
definitions.example: The noise was so loud that she woke up.

definitions.definition: Introducing a premise or supposition for consideration: seeing as; inasmuch as; given that; as would appear from the fact that.
Introducing a subordinate clause modifying an adverb.
definitions.example: How often did she visit him? — Twice that I saw.

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a desire or wish.
definitions.example: Oh that spring would come!

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a strong emotion such as sadness or surprise.

definitions.definition: n	Initialism of field Of research.

definitions.definition: Useful or helpful.
definitions.example: We made quick progress, due to favourable winds.

definitions.definition: Convenient or at a suitable time; opportune.

definitions.definition: Auspicious or lucky.

definitions.definition: With a comparative or with more and a verb phrase, establishes a correlation with one or more other such comparatives.

definitions.definition: With a comparative, and often with for it, indicates a result more like said comparative. This can be negated with none. See none the.

definitions.definition: Offspring.
Lineage.
A difficult return or block of a shot.
Something gained; an acquisition.
(ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.

definitions.definition: To receive.

definitions.definition: (in a perfect construction, with present-tense meaning) To have. See usage notes.

definitions.definition: To fetch, bring, take.

definitions.definition: To become, or cause oneself to become.
definitions.example: I'm getting hungry; how about you?

definitions.definition: To cause to become; to bring about.

definitions.definition: To cause to do.
definitions.example: I can't get it to work.

definitions.definition: To cause to come or go or move.

definitions.definition: To cause to be in a certain status or position.
definitions.example: Get him here at once.

definitions.definition: (with various prepositions, such as into, over, or behind; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries get into, get over, etc.) To adopt, assume, arrive at, or progress towards (a certain position, location, state).

definitions.definition: To cover (a certain distance) while travelling.

definitions.definition: To begin (doing something or to do something).

definitions.definition: To take or catch (a scheduled transportation service).
definitions.example: I normally get the 7:45 train.

definitions.definition: To respond to (a telephone call, a doorbell, etc).
definitions.example: Can you get that call, please? I'm busy.

definitions.definition: (followed by infinitive) To be able, be permitted, or have the opportunity (to do something desirable or ironically implied to be desirable).

definitions.definition: To understand. (compare get it)
definitions.example: I don't get what you mean by "fun". This place sucks!

definitions.definition: To be told; be the recipient of (a question, comparison, opinion, etc.).
definitions.example: "You look just like Helen Mirren." / "I get that a lot."

definitions.definition: To be. Used to form the passive of verbs.
definitions.example: He got bitten by a dog.

definitions.definition: To become ill with or catch (a disease).

definitions.definition: To catch out, trick successfully.
definitions.example: He keeps calling pretending to be my boss—it gets me every time.

definitions.definition: To perplex, stump.

definitions.definition: To find as an answer.
definitions.example: What did you get for question four?

definitions.definition: To bring to reckoning; to catch (as a criminal); to effect retribution.
definitions.example: I'm gonna get him for that.

definitions.definition: To hear completely; catch.
definitions.example: Sorry, I didn't get that. Could you repeat it?

definitions.definition: To getter.
definitions.example: I put the getter into the container to get the gases.

definitions.definition: To beget (of a father).
To learn; to commit to memory; to memorize; sometimes with out.

definitions.definition: Used with a personal pronoun to indicate that someone is being pretentious or grandiose.
definitions.example: Get her with her new hairdo.

definitions.definition: To go, to leave; to scram.
To kill.
definitions.example: They’re coming to get you, Barbara.

definitions.definition: To make acquisitions; to gain; to profit.
To measure.
definitions.example: Did you get her temperature?

To float.

Disappearing, vanishing.

The territory of a nation, especially an independent nation state or formerly independent nation; a political entity asserting ultimate authority over a geographical area; a sovereign state.

The rock through which a vein runs.
The female genitalia, especially the vagina.

definitions.definition: To possess, own.

definitions.definition: To hold, as something at someone's disposal.

definitions.definition: Used to state the existence or presence of someone in a specified relationship with the subject.

definitions.definition: To partake of (a particular substance, especially food or drink, or action or activity).

definitions.definition: To be scheduled to attend, undertake or participate in.

definitions.definition: To experience, go through, undergo.

definitions.definition: To be afflicted with, suffer from.

definitions.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a past participle) Used in forming the perfect aspect.
definitions.example: I had already eaten.

definitions.definition: To defeat in a fight; take.

definitions.definition: (obsolete outside Ireland) To be able to speak (a language).

definitions.definition: To trick, to deceive.

definitions.definition: (often used in the negative) To believe, buy, be taken in by.

definitions.definition: (manner) In accordance with the facts; truthfully, accurately.
(modal) Honestly, genuinely, in fact, really.

definitions.definition: (degree) Very.
definitions.example: You are truly silly.

You are truly silly.

definitions.definition: To become fastened in place.

definitions.definition: To fasten with a lock.
definitions.example: Remember to lock the door when you leave.

definitions.definition: To be capable of becoming fastened in place.
definitions.example: This door locks with a key.

definitions.definition: To intertwine or dovetail.
definitions.example: We locked arms and stepped out into the night.

definitions.definition: (break dancing) To freeze one's body or a part thereof in place.
definitions.example: a pop and lock routine

definitions.definition: To furnish (a canal) with locks.
To raise or lower (a boat) in a lock.
To seize (e.g. the sword arm of an antagonist) by turning the left arm around it, to disarm him.
To modify (a thread) so that users cannot make new posts in it.
(WMF jargon) To prevent a page from being edited by other users.
definitions.example: Frequently vandalized pages are generally locked to prevent further damage.

definitions.definition: Having undergone locking; secured by a lock.
definitions.example: A locked door barred the way.

definitions.definition: (Dublin) Very drunk.
(of a phone) Bound to a carrier.

definitions.definition: The present time.
definitions.example: Now is the right time.

definitions.definition: (often with "the") The state of not paying attention to the future or the past.
definitions.example: She is living in the now.

definitions.definition: (chiefly in phenomenology) A particular instant in time, as perceived at that instant.
Present; current.
Fashionable; popular; up to date; current.
definitions.example: I think this band's sound is very now.

definitions.definition: At the time the will is written. Used in order to prevent any inheritance from being transferred to a person of a future marriage. Does not indicate the existence of a previous marriage.
definitions.example: Now wife.

definitions.definition: At the present time.
definitions.example: Now I am six.

definitions.definition: (sentence) Used to introduce a point, a qualification of what has previously been said, a remonstration or a rebuke.
definitions.example: Now stop that, Jimmy!

definitions.definition: Differently from the immediate past; differently from a more remote past or a possible future; differently from all other times.
definitions.example: Now I am ready.

definitions.definition: Differently from the situation before a stated event or change of circumstance.
definitions.example: Now all the children have grown up and left, the house is very quiet.

definitions.definition: At the time reached within a narration.
definitions.example: He now asked her whether she had made pudding.

definitions.definition: In the context of urgency.
definitions.example: Now listen, we must do something about this.

definitions.definition: As 'but now': Very recently; not long ago; up to the present.
Since, because, in light of the fact; often with that.
definitions.example: Now that we're all here, let's start the meeting.

definitions.definition: Indicates a signal to begin.
definitions.example: Now! Fire all we've got while the enemy is in reach!

definitions.definition: The greatest amount.
definitions.example: The most I can offer for the house is $150,000.

definitions.definition: The greater part.
definitions.example: Most of the penguins were friendly and curious.

definitions.definition: A record-setting amount.
Forms the superlative of many adjectives.
definitions.example: Correctness is most important.

definitions.definition: To a great extent or degree; highly; very.
definitions.example: This is a most unusual specimen.

definitions.definition: Superlative of many
Superlative of much
The greater part of a group, especially a group of people.
definitions.example: Most want the best for their children.

definitions.definition: The game of tag, or it, in which the player attempting to catch the others is called "he".
The player attempting to catch the others in this game.
A male.
definitions.example: Is your cat a he or a she?

definitions.definition: (personal) A male person or animal already known or implied.
(personal, sometimes proscribed, see usage notes) A person whose gender is unknown or irrelevant.
definitions.example: The rulebook clearly states that "if any student is caught cheating, he will be expelled", and you were caught cheating, were you not, Anna?

definitions.definition: (personal) An animal whose gender is unknown.
A genderless object regarded as masculine, such as certain stars (e.g. Sun, Mercury, Mars, Jupiter) or certain ships.

examples: Is your cat a he or a she?
The rulebook clearly states that "if any student is caught cheating, he will be expelled", and you were caught cheating, were you not, Anna?

definitions.definition: A wealthy or privileged person.
One who has some (contextually specified) thing.
To possess, own.
definitions.example: I have a house and a car.

definitions.definition: To hold, as something at someone's disposal.
definitions.example: Do you have the key? (not necessarily one's own key)

definitions.definition: Used to state the existence or presence of someone in a specified relationship with the subject.
definitions.example: I have a really mean boss.

definitions.definition: To partake of (a particular substance, especially food or drink, or action or activity).
definitions.example: Can I have a look at that?

definitions.definition: To be scheduled to attend, undertake or participate in.
definitions.example: Fred won't be able to come to the party; he has a meeting that day.

definitions.definition: To experience, go through, undergo.
definitions.example: He had surgery on his hip yesterday.

definitions.definition: To be afflicted with, suffer from.
definitions.example: He had a cold last week.

definitions.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a past participle) Used in forming the perfect aspect.
definitions.example: I had already eaten.

definitions.definition: Used as an interrogative verb before a pronoun to form a tag question, echoing a previous use of 'have' as an auxiliary verb or, in certain cases, main verb. (For further discussion, see the appendix English tag questions.)
definitions.example: They haven't eaten dinner yet, have they?

definitions.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a to-infinitive) See have to.
definitions.example: I have to go.

definitions.definition: To give birth to.
definitions.example: My mother had me when she was 25.

definitions.definition: To engage in sexual intercourse with.
definitions.example: He's always bragging about how many women he's had.

definitions.definition: To accept as a romantic partner.
definitions.example: Despite my protestations of love, she would not have me.

definitions.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To cause to, by a command, request or invitation.
definitions.example: They had me feed their dog while they were out of town.

definitions.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To cause to be.
definitions.example: He had him arrested for trespassing.

definitions.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To be affected by an occurrence. (Used in supplying a topic that is not a verb argument.)
definitions.example: I've had three people today tell me my hair looks nice.

definitions.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To depict as being.
definitions.example: Their stories differed; he said he'd been at work when the incident occurred, but her statement had him at home that entire evening.

definitions.definition: To defeat in a fight; take.
definitions.example: I could have him!

definitions.definition: (obsolete outside Ireland) To be able to speak (a language).
definitions.example: I have no German.

definitions.definition: To feel or be (especially painfully) aware of.
definitions.example: Dan certainly has arms today, probably from scraping paint off four columns the day before.

definitions.definition: To trick, to deceive.
definitions.example: You had me alright! I never would have thought that was just a joke.

definitions.definition: (often with present participle) To allow; to tolerate.
definitions.example: I asked my dad if I could go to the concert this Thursday, but he wouldn't have it since it's a school night.

definitions.definition: (often used in the negative) To believe, buy, be taken in by.
definitions.example: I made up an excuse as to why I was out so late, but my wife wasn't having any of it.

definitions.definition: To host someone; to take in as a guest.
definitions.example: Thank you for having me!

definitions.definition: To get a reading, measurement, or result from an instrument or calculation.
definitions.example: I have two contacts on my scope.

definitions.definition: (of a jury) To consider a court proceeding that has been completed; to begin deliberations on a case.
definitions.example: We'll schedule closing arguments for Thursday, and the jury will have the case by that afternoon.

definitions.definition: To make an observation of (a bird species).

Eternal.
Not affected by time; ageless.
Done at an improper time; unseasonable; untimely.
Not decreasing over time in quality and appeal.

definitions.definition: A large, naturally-occurring cavity formed underground or in the face of a cliff or a hillside.
definitions.example: We found a cave on the mountainside where we could take shelter.

definitions.definition: A hole, depression, or gap in earth or rock, whether natural or man-made.
A storage cellar, especially for wine or cheese.
definitions.example: This wine has been aged in our cave for thirty years.

definitions.definition: A place of retreat, such as a man cave.
definitions.example: My room was a cozy cave where I could escape from my family.

definitions.definition: A naturally-occurring cavity in bedrock which is large enough to be entered by an adult.
definitions.example: It was not strictly a cave, but a narrow fissure in the rock.

definitions.definition: A shielded area where nuclear experiments can be carried out.
(drilling) Debris, particularly broken rock, which falls into a drill hole and interferes with drilling.
A collapse or cave-in.
The vagina.
(often "Cave") A group that breaks from a larger political party or faction on a particular issue.
Any hollow place, or part; a cavity.
A code cave.
To surrender.
definitions.example: He caved under pressure.

definitions.definition: To collapse.
definitions.example: First the braces buckled, then the roof began to cave, then we ran.

definitions.definition: To hollow out or undermine.
definitions.example: The levee has been severely caved by the river current.

definitions.definition: To engage in the recreational exploration of caves.
definitions.example: I have caved from Yugoslavia to Kentucky.

definitions.definition: In room-and-pillar mining, to extract a deposit of rock by breaking down a pillar which had been holding it in place.

definitions.definition: To work over tailings to dress small pieces of marketable ore.
To dwell in a cave.

definitions.definition: A short circuit.
A short film.
A short version of a garment in a particular size.

definitions.definition: A shortstop.

definitions.definition: A short seller.
definitions.example: The market decline was terrible, but the shorts were buying champagne.

definitions.definition: A short sale.
definitions.example: He closed out his short at a modest loss after three months.

definitions.definition: A summary account.
A short sound, syllable, or vowel.
An integer variable having a smaller range than normal integers; usually two bytes long.
An automobile; especially in crack shorts, to break into automobiles.
To cause a short circuit in (something).
Of an electrical circuit, to short circuit.
To shortchange.
To provide with a smaller than agreed or labeled amount.

definitions.definition: To sell something, especially securities, that one does not own at the moment for delivery at a later date in hopes of profiting from a decline in the price; to sell short.
To shorten.
Having a small distance from one end or edge to another, either horizontally or vertically.
(of a person) Of comparatively small height.
Having little duration.
definitions.example: Our meeting was a short six minutes today. Every day for the past month it’s been at least twenty minutes long.

definitions.definition: (followed by for) Of a word or phrase, constituting an abbreviation (for another) or shortened form (of another).
definitions.example: “Phone” is short for “telephone” and "asap" short for "as soon as possible".

definitions.definition: (of a fielder or fielding position) that is relatively close to the batsman.
(of a ball) that bounced relatively far from the batsman.
(of an approach shot or putt) that falls short of the green or the hole.
(of pastries) Brittle, crumbly, especially due to the use of a large quantity of fat. (See shortbread, shortcake, shortcrust, shortening.)
Abrupt; brief; pointed; petulant.
definitions.example: He gave a short answer to the question.

definitions.definition: Limited in quantity; inadequate; insufficient; scanty.

definitions.definition: Insufficiently provided; inadequately supplied, especially with money; scantily furnished; lacking.
definitions.example: I'd lend you the cash but I'm a little short at present.

definitions.definition: Deficient; less; not coming up to a measure or standard.
definitions.example: an account which is short of the truth

definitions.definition: Undiluted; neat.
Not distant in time; near at hand.
Being in a financial investment position that is structured to be profitable if the price of the underlying security declines in the future.
definitions.example: I'm short General Motors because I think their sales are plunging.

definitions.definition: Abruptly, curtly, briefly.
definitions.example: He cut me short repeatedly in the meeting.

definitions.definition: Unawares.
definitions.example: The recent developments at work caught them short.

definitions.definition: Without achieving a goal or requirement.
definitions.example: His speech fell short of what was expected.

definitions.definition: (of the manner of bounce of a cricket ball) Relatively far from the batsman and hence bouncing higher than normal; opposite of full.
With a negative ownership position.

definitions.definition: Deficient in.
definitions.example: He's short common sense.

definitions.definition: Having a negative position in.
definitions.example: I don’t want to be short the market going into the weekend.

definitions.definition: Shared in confidence.

definitions.definition: Combined (by effort or ownership).

An unsought, unintended, and/or unexpected, but fortunate, discovery and/or learning experience that happens by accident.
The mental ability to recover quickly from depression, illness or misfortune.
The physical property of material that can resume its shape after being stretched or deformed; elasticity.

The positive capacity of an organizational system or company to adapt and return to equilibrium due to the consequences of a crisis or failure caused by any type of disruption, including: an outage, natural disasters, man-made disasters, terrorism, or similar (particularly IT systems, archives).
